issue.title: There seems to be no way of getting all images for certain forms?
issue.body:
I apologize if this mentioned somewhere, I'm new to the the API. But I didn't see any clear answer to this in the docs or in existing issues. It seems like there's images for certain forms that are not exposed by the API directly. I namely noticed this with Deerling, but it almost certainly applies elsewhere

If you check https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon/deerling, the `sprites` field only has data for the default (spring) form. The Pokemon has 3 other forms however:

- https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon-form/10068 (summer)
- https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon-form/10069 (autumn)
- https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon-form/10070 (winter)

Each of these forms does have a `sprites` field as well, but they contain considerably less images than the `pokemon` endpoint provides, only providing the default sprites

Despite this, images for other platforms DO exist for these forms. Such as:

- https://github.com/PokeAPI/sprites/blob/master/sprites/pokemon/versions/generation-vi/x-y/585-summer.png
- https://github.com/PokeAPI/sprites/blob/master/sprites/pokemon/versions/generation-vi/x-y/585-autumn.png
- https://github.com/PokeAPI/sprites/blob/master/sprites/pokemon/versions/generation-vi/x-y/585-winter.png

But it seems like these images are not exposed by the API? The `pokemon-form` endpoints all point back to the same base form (spring), and none of the alternate forms seem to have dedicated `pokemon` entries

I suspect this issue applies to all Pokemon with multiple forms where the forms do not have dedicated `pokemon` entries, not just Deerling. I also noticed this same issue with Flabebe, as if has multiple forms and images for other platforms but seemingly no way to get the images from the API?

issue.title: Add magic 8ball app
issue.body:
Adds an app emulating a magic 8 ball. Who needs AI when you can get an answer to any* question this easily?
<sub>* As long as it's a yes/no question.</sub>

### Features

- Answers yes/no questions
- Has some maybe funny answers
- Has multiple answer pools
- Pretty versatile internal structure for adding your own answers

### Images

![8ball in infinisim saying "your question is important to us"](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/804a698f-aa76-4340-9321-399c4a185dc7)
![8ball in infinisim with the menu open](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2d14ea4b-6dd8-48f8-817b-67f7d081545e)
![Asking the 8ball if my code works and it saying no](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d376d192-1dbc-451f-a19e-f742b7dc4cad)

### Usage

Ask your yes/no question and shake the watch (or double tap) to get an answer. 

Long tapping brings up a menu which allows you to choose the answer pool. They are as follows:
- Default: Has approx. 2:1 chance of showing one of the answers I wrote versus an original 8ball answer. Has a rare chance to show a nonsense silly answer.
- OG: Just the 20 original 8ball answers.
- Fair: Has an equal chance to give a yes or a no answer (default and OG have a 2:1 ratio of yes:no answers). Has a rare chance to show a nonsense silly answer.
- Rig - Yes: Same as Default, but no answers are replaced with yes and has no silly answers.
- Rig - No: Same as Default, but yes answers are replaced with no and has no silly answers.
- Cat: I blame my brother.

### Development

To add your own answers, add them to the relevant vector in the categories variable in Magic8ball.h. Don't worry about affecting chances by adding more, the number of answers in a category doesn't affect its weight. That's managed by answerPools further down.

To add your own category, you need to add a new value to enum CategoryType, a new entry in the categories map (must have at least 1 answer associated with it (note the text sizing guide above categories)), and add this CategoryType to the relevant pools in answerPools. You may also add new entries to answerPools, they'll automatically show up in the long tap menu.

### References

The original 8ball answers were pulled from [https://magic-8ball.com/magic-8-ball-answers/](https://magic-8ball.com/magic-8-ball-answers/).

I'm on the same page. I do occasionally see t.me links used as C2 dead drops for malware, which I feel is the only instance that such links would be appropriate here. Like I said in #870, I need to see compelling evidence to add links, as in verifiable proof to support the claims. As an example, consider how steam profiles are used in #726 or how telegram bots are used for exfil in #880 for what I'd be willing to consider, and I didn't add either to those PRs. > Just open the links from telegram and you will see, it’s definitely all fraudolent, but at this point feel free to add what you think it’s sketchier 1.) would require me to set up a telegram sockpuppet 2.) would require me to investigate to support your addition, your PR should include the evidence for us to review not make more work for us. (What changes might users need to make in their application due to this PR?) 프로젝트 하위 패키지구조를 바꾸었습니다. presentation 하위에 디자인 시스템을 생성해 테마를 이동했으며, view를 추가해 목적을 가진 뷰와 컴포넌트로 구분했습니다. 이 부분에 이견이 있으시면 이번 PR에 의견 남겨주시면 감사하겠습니다. ```markdown feelin ┣ presentation ┃ ┣ designsystem ┃ ┃ ┗ theme ┃ ┃ ┃ ┗ (기존 테마 파일) ┃ ┗ view ┃ ┃ ┣ community ┃ ┃ ┃ ┗ (커뮤니티 뷰 구현 파일) ┃ ┃ ┗ component ┃ ┃ ┃ ┣ note ┃ ┃ ┃ ┃ ┗ (커뮤니티 뷰 중 노트 컴포넌트 구현 파일) ┃ ┃ ┃ ┗ profile ┃ ┃ ┃ ┃ ┗ (노트 컴포넌트 중 프로파일 아이콘 구현 파일) ┣ util ┃ ┗ ... ┗ MainActivity.kt ``` ## ScreenShots (If needed)

## Other information: 이번 PR 내용은 아니지만, 레포지토리 설명 바꾸신 부분이 마음에 듭니다.

+// Package github provides a GitHub MCP server implementation for GitHub API operations.
+package github
+
+import (
+	"context"
+	"fmt"
+	"net/http"
+	"strconv"
+	"strings"
+	"time"
+
+	"github.com/google/go-github/v55/github"
+
+	"github.com/ondatra-ai/flow-test-go/pkg/errors"
+	"github.com/ondatra-ai/flow-test-go/pkg/types"
+)
+
+// Provider implements the GitHub MCP server provider.
+type Provider struct {
+	client *github.Client
+	token  string
+}
+
+// Config holds the configuration for the GitHub provider.
+type Config struct {
+	Token string `json:"token"`
+}
+
+// tokenTransport implements http.RoundTripper to add GitHub token authentication.
+type tokenTransport struct {
+	Token string
+	Base  http.RoundTripper
+}
+
+// RoundTrip implements http.RoundTripper interface to add Authorization header.
+func (t tokenTransport) RoundTrip(req *http.Request) (*http.Response, error) {
+	cloned := req.Clone(req.Context())
+	cloned.Header.Set("Authorization", "token "+t.Token)
+
+	response, err := t.base().RoundTrip(cloned)
+	if err != nil {
+		return nil, fmt.Errorf("GitHub API request failed: %w", err)
+	}
+
+	return response, nil
+}
+
+// base returns the base transport, defaulting to http.DefaultTransport.
+func (t tokenTransport) base() http.RoundTripper {
+	if t.Base != nil {
+		return t.Base
+	}
+
+	return http.DefaultTransport
+}
+
+// New creates a new GitHub provider with the given token.
+func New(token string) (*Provider, error) {
+	if token == "" {
+		return nil, &types.ExecutionError{
+			Code:        "GITHUB_TOKEN_REQUIRED",
+			Message:     "GitHub token is required",
+			Details:     nil,
+			Recoverable: false,
+			Timestamp:   time.Now(),
+			StackTrace:  "",
+		}
+	}
+
+	// Create HTTP client with token authentication
+	httpClient := &http.Client{
+		Transport:     tokenTransport{Token: token, Base: nil},

pull_request.title: [Issue #49] User Story 2.3: GitHub MCP Server — github_get_issue (Template-Conformant)
pull_request.body:
- Implement in-process github MCP provider
- Expose github_get_issue tool constrained to GitHub.com
- Add token authentication with proper redaction
- Classify API errors (401/403 → fatal, 429 → retryable)
- Add unit and e2e tests
- Add static error definitions for GitHub provider to fix golangci-lint err113 violations
- Move environment variable resolution to shared ResolveEnvVar function in types package
- Update GitHub provider to use wrapped static errors instead of dynamic errors
- Add environment variable resolution to MCP server configuration
- Update GitHub provider tests to match new error message format
- Improve GitHub integration test to verify actual tool execution flow

**Related Issue**: #49: GitHub Reader Step Implementation

Implements GitHub MCP provider exposing github_get_issue tool with proper error handling, linting compliance, and comprehensive testing. The provider includes token authentication, error classification, and environment variable resolution for secure configuration management.

## Acceptance Criteria

[✓] Provider registers github_get_issue tool
[✓] Only api.github.com domain accepted
[✓] Success: Returns { title, body, state, labels } in Result and ContextWrites
[✓] Errors: Classified and written to ContextWrites.last_error
[✓] Tokens redacted from logs
[✓] Unit tests pass
[✓] All linting issues resolved with static error definitions
[✓] Environment variable resolution implemented
[ ] E2E tests pass with real GitHub API (requires .env.e2e with GITHUB_TOKEN)

## Implementation Details

- Created internal/github/provider.go with GitHub REST v3 client
- Added comprehensive parameter validation and error classification
- Implemented custom token transport for authentication
- Registered provider in MCP registry
- Added static error definitions to resolve golangci-lint violations
- Moved environment variable resolution to shared types package
- Added unit tests covering all validation scenarios
- Added e2e test framework (passes tool discovery, execution requires credentials)


<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->
## Summary by CodeRabbit

* **New Features**
  * GitHub integration: new MCP provider and github_get_issue tool to fetch issue details (title, body, state, labels).
  * MCP server configs support environment-variable placeholders (e.g., {env.VAR}) resolved at runtime.

* **Refactor**
  * Centralized environment-variable resolution into a shared ResolveEnvVar utility.

* **Tests**
  * Added unit and end-to-end tests for GitHub provider, env-var resolution, and tool execution.

* **Chores**
  * Go toolchain and dependency updates; added GitHub client dependencies.
<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->

issue.title: Add new SQL Server role management commands (Get-SqlDscRole, New-SqlDscRole, Remove-SqlDscRole)
issue.body: This PR implements three new public commands for managing SQL Server roles, addressing the need for programmatic server role operations using the SMO ServerRole API. ## New Commands ### Get-SqlDscRole Retrieves server roles from a SQL Server Database Engine instance with support for: - Getting all server roles when no name is specified - Getting a specific role by name - Refreshing the server's roles collection before retrieval - Pipeline input support ```powershell $serverObject = Connect-SqlDscDatabaseEngine -InstanceName 'MyInstance' $allRoles = $serverObject | Get-SqlDscRole $specificRole = $serverObject | Get-SqlDscRole -Name 'MyCustomRole' ``` ### New-SqlDscRole Creates new server roles in a SQL Server Database Engine instance with support for: - Setting the role owner during creation - Force parameter to bypass confirmation prompts - Validation to prevent creating duplicate roles - ShouldProcess support for safe operations ```powershell $serverObject = Connect-SqlDscDatabaseEngine -InstanceName 'MyInstance' $newRole = $serverObject | New-SqlDscRole -Name 'MyCustomRole' -Owner 'MyOwner' ``` ### Remove-SqlDscRole Removes server roles from a SQL Server Database Engine instance with support for: - Two parameter sets: by server object + name or by role object - Protection against removing built-in roles (validates `IsFixedRole` property) - Force parameter to bypass confirmation prompts - ShouldProcess support with high impact confirmation ```powershell $serverObject = Connect-SqlDscDatabaseEngine -InstanceName 'MyInstance' $serverObject | Remove-SqlDscRole -Name 'MyCustomRole' -Force # Or using role object $role = $serverObject | Get-SqlDscRole -Name 'MyCustomRole' $role | Remove-SqlDscRole -Force ``` ## Implementation Details - **Follows existing module patterns**: Uses the same error handling, localization, and SMO integration patterns as other commands in the module - **Comprehensive error handling**: Includes proper exception handling with localized error messages using `New-InvalidOperationException` - **Type safety**: Uses strongly-typed SMO objects (`Microsoft.SqlServer.Management.Smo.ServerRole`) for all operations - **Localization support**: All user-facing strings are localized using the module's string resource system - **Full test coverage**: 33 comprehensive unit tests covering all scenarios including success paths, error conditions, parameter validation, and edge cases ## SMO Integration The commands leverage the existing SMO infrastructure in the module: - Uses `Microsoft.SqlServer.Management.Smo.ServerRole` objects - Integrates with the server's `Roles` collection - Follows SMO patterns for object creation (`New-Object` + `.Create()`) and deletion (`.Drop()`) - Supports role property management including `Owner` and `IsFixedRole` validation All commands follow the module's naming convention using the `SqlDsc` prefix and `Role` noun as specified in the requirements. --- 💡 You can make Copilot smarter by setting up custom instructions, customizing its development environment and configuring Model Context Protocol (MCP) servers. Learn more [Copilot coding agent tips](https://gh.io/copilot-coding-agent-tips) in the docs. - - - This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/dsccommunity/SqlServerDsc/2137)

pull_request.title: Test Coverage for post-release & pre-release & associated post-fix merge branch fix
pull_request.body:
Looking over github actions, there didn't seem to be a good way to "test" them.  Most defer the action to a script and then test that script.  However, these actions make heavy use of git & there isn't a practical way to test them ... other than using Git.  I've added a basic mock framework to assist in testing our git actions so going forward we can expand test coverage.  I've started with adding tests for the pre & post release actions.  

I went down this path because of this failure: https://github.com/apache/grails-core/actions/runs/16727197839/job/47769435724 

This PR should resolve this failure - the issue was the action wasn't stripping the refs/heads from the refspec to checkout the associated branch for update.

issue.title: Support for DuckDB
issue.body:
<!---
Please don't remove the template.
Please be sure the feature does not yet exist with the latest HeidiSQL build from https://www.heidisql.com/download.php#nightlybuilds
-->

**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
No problem, except that my favorite DB GUI doesn't support this database yet.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
DuckDB is a lot like Sqlite, but optimized for analytical processing. It's also completely free. It would just be very nice if HeidiSQL supported this database type too. Information can be found here:

https://duckdb.org/

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
I'm using commandline and the built-in webgui. This works, but not great. DBeaver and Beekeeper studio support it too.
